if we define rule in ingress resource does alb also create sam rules in alb?

Yes! That's exactly what ALB Controller does:

You write Ingress resource (YAML)
        ↓
ALB Controller reads it
        ↓
Automatically creates same rules in AWS ALB

------------------------------------------------------
Example:

# You write this
rules:
  - host: api.myapp.com
    http:
      paths:
      - path: /users  → users-service
      - path: /orders → orders-service
---
ALB Controller automatically creates:
--
AWS ALB Console
└── Listeners
    └── 80/443
        └── Rules
            ├── IF host = api.myapp.com AND path = /users  → forward to users-service ✅
            ├── IF host = api.myapp.com AND path = /orders → forward to orders-service ✅
            └── default → 404
---------------------------------------------------------------

That's the magic of ALB Controller:

Without ALB Controller:
→ manually create ALB
→ manually add each rule in AWS console
→ painful for 100s of services ❌

With ALB Controller:
→ just write Ingress YAML
→ ALB rules created automatically ✅
→ update YAML → ALB rules update automatically ✅
→ delete YAML → ALB rules deleted automatically ✅

------------------------------------------------------
NGINX Controller works differently:

NGINX Controller:
→ does NOT create anything in AWS
→ NGINX pod itself handles the routing
→ rules live inside NGINX config, not AWS ✅
--------------------------------------------------------
how many max rules one alb have?

one ALB can have 100 rules (excluding default rules), but this is adjustable — you can request an increase from AWS. amazon

Full ALB limits:

Rules per ALB          → 100 (adjustable) ✅
Listeners per ALB      → 50
Targets per ALB        → 1,000
Target Groups per ALB  → 100

means one alb can have 400plus rules

Yes! Since it's adjustable, you can request AWS to increase beyond 100:

Default limit  → 100 rules
After request  → 200, 300, 400+ rules ✅

AWS Console
→ Service Quotas
→ Elastic Load Balancing
→ Rules per Application Load Balancer
→ Request quota increase
→ Enter desired value (e.g. 500)
→ Submit ✅
--------------------------
This is why your company uses NGINX instead of ALB:

Your company → 400+ services
ALB limit    → 100 rules per ALB

With ALB:
→ need 4+ ALBs for 400 services
→ expensive ❌

With NGINX:
→ unlimited rules in NGINX config
→ single NLB + NGINX handles all 400 services
→ cost effective ✅
